1Ô∏è‚É£ Basic Linux Commands
Command	Description
pwd	Displays the current working directory
ls	Lists files and directories
cd <directory>	Changes directory
mkdir <folder>	Creates a new directory
rmdir <folder>	Deletes an empty directory
rm <file>	Deletes a file
rm -r <folder>	Deletes a directory and its contents

EG:
  mkdir my_folder  # Creates a folder named 'my_folder'
  cd my_folder     # Navigates into 'my_folder'
  pwd             # Shows the current directory
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2Ô∏è‚É£ File Management Commands
Command	Description
touch <file>	Creates a new empty file
cat <file>	Displays file content
nano <file>	Opens file in Nano editor
vi <file>	Opens file in Vi editor
cp <source> <destination>	Copies file or folder
mv <source> <destination>	Moves or renames a file
rm <file>	Deletes a file

EG:
   touch file.txt  # Creates an empty file
   echo "Hello" > file.txt  # Writes "Hello" into file.txt
   cat file.txt  # Displays contents of file.txt
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

3Ô∏è‚É£ User Management Commands
Command	Description
whoami	---Shows the current logged-in user
who	 --- Displays all logged-in users
id <username> -	Displays user ID and group ID
adduser <username> ---	Creates a new user
deluser <username> ---	Deletes a user
passwd <username> -	---Changes a user's password
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4Ô∏è‚É£ Process Management Commands
Command	Description
ps	--- Lists currently running processes
top	--- Shows system resource usage
kill <PID>	---- Terminates a process by PID
killall <name>	--- Kills all processes with a specific name
pkill <name> ---	Kills processes by name
htop -	Interactive process manager (install with sudo apt install htop)
EG:
   ps aux  # Shows all running processes
   kill 1234  # Kills the process with PID 1234

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5Ô∏è‚É£ Disk Management Commands
Command	Description
df -h	 ---Displays disk usage
du -sh --- <directory>	Shows folder size
lsblk	---Lists storage devices
mount /dev/sdX /mnt	 --- Mounts a partition
umount /mnt ----	Unmounts a partition
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6Ô∏è‚É£ Networking Commands
Command	Description
ping <website>	---Checks network connectivity
curl <URL>	---Fetches a webpage or API data
wget <URL>---	Downloads a file from the web
ifconfig -----	Shows IP address (deprecated)
ip a	---Displays network interfaces
netstat -tulnp	---Shows open network ports
EG:
ping google.com  # Tests connectivity to Google
wget example.com/file.zip  # Downloads a file from example.com

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

7Ô∏è‚É£ Permissions & Ownership Commands
Command	Description
chmod 777 <file> ---	Changes file permissions
chown user:group <file>	----Changes file ownership
ls -l---	Shows file permissions
EG:
  chmod 755 script.sh  # Gives read/write/execute to the owner and read/execute to others
  chown user1 file.txt  # Changes ownership of file.txt to user1
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8Ô∏è‚É£ Package Management Commands
Command	Description
sudo apt update	----Updates package lists (Debian-based)
sudo apt upgrade	----Upgrades installed packages
sudo apt install <package> ----	Installs a package (Debian)
sudo yum install <package>	----Installs a package (RHEL-based)
sudo pacman -S <package>	----Installs a package (Arch-based)
dpkg -i <file.deb>	-----Installs a .deb package manually
Example:
sudo apt update  # Updates package index
sudo apt install git  # Installs Git
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
9Ô∏è‚É£ System Monitoring Commands
Command	Description
uptime	---Shows system uptime
free -h	---Displays memory usage
vmstat	----Shows CPU, memory, and disk stats
iostat	---Displays CPU and I/O stats
dmesg	----Shows system boot logs
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
üîü Important Shortcuts
Shortcut	Description
Ctrl + C	---Stops a running command
Ctrl + Z	---Suspends a process
Ctrl + R	---Searches command history
Ctrl + L	----Clears the terminal
Tab	-----Auto-completes commands
!!	---Runs the last command
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üöÄ Summary
Category         	Commands
